in real life.</Para><Para>It is one of the rare pockets of positivism right now. With the world embroiled in identity politics, black pride is on the ascendance as everyone's tongue is tripping over such names as T'Challa aka The Black Panther; Shuri, his technologically savvy sister; and Okoye, the bald fighter .</Para><Para>Thank goodness too for Young Fathers, the Liberian-Nigerian-Scottish experimental hip-hop trio who have upended genres and expectations ever since their Mercury Prize-winning debut, Dead (2014). The follow-up, White Men Are Black Men Too (2015), is an even more abrasive cocktail of politics and avant-rock.</Para><Para>Their latest, Cocoa Sugar, is timelier, championing 21st-century multiculturalism steeped in contemporaneous issues regarding race, identity and social justice.</Para><Para>Designed by British artist Tom Hingston, the striking cover artwork is an image of member Alloysious Massaquoi manipulated to look like Grace Jones. It is also a nod to the iconoclastic aesthetics of the 1980s Brit design collective called Buffalo, who mixed sportswear and worldly threads into an urban, post-punk, post-gender look.</Para><Para>Cocoa Sugar oozes the immediacy and drama of these decade-leaping allusions, as well as the rebellious streak underlying their exigent agendas.</Para><Para>Compared with their earlier releases, Cocoa Sugar slips down the throat better, but you detect strange, exotic flavours.</Para><Para>The opening track, See How, rides on a catchy melody riff, but it is constantly hijacked by a thumping of a door, or a rude toot of a car horn. The sentiments are surprisingly irony-free: "Someday I'll be a star/ That's shining bright in the sky... Give me lovers/So I may have my pleasures/And not lose my heart/In this squalor."</Para><Para>It is this juxtaposition of resilience and abject bleakness that energises Young Fathers' contrarian armoury of studio wizardry.</Para><Para>Fee Fi is another excellent counterpoint of light and heavy. A backing chorus revels in a call-and-response childhood game, but it is not a game once you make out the lyrics. "So you think you gonna run/Fee fi fo fum," goes one line. "Don't you know I got a gun?/Fee fi fo fum," is a rejoinder. The music is part gypsy jazz, part rap, and part Tom Waits-styled Delta blues, and then some.</Para><Para>Such is the irresistible allure of Young Fathers. With their sleight-of-hand approach, they embrace the ambivalences that exist in an increasingly polarised world. In My View is an instant humdinger driven by a motorik beat and you would dance along, none the wiser until you realise it is taking a sledgehammer against machismo.</Para><Para>"I wanna be a king until I am/A man is just a man I understand/ Has everything gone to plan?" goes one reality check even as the song climaxes in a triumphant display of Brazilian-styled street repercussion.</Para><Para>It is dance, dance, revolution, tearing down demagoguery, sexual stereotyping and other walls of division.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Yeow Kai Chai </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

